<subSubSection id="02C66578FFFBFFBAFF3D9D4569C67F59" pageId="22" pageNumber="36" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFFBFFBAFF3D9D456B7A7C18" blockId="22.[151,756,257,568]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFFBFFBAFF3D9D4568057C78" bold="true" box="[151,264,257,281]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">Remarks:</emphasis>
It is distinguished by having an elongated and compressed test with the early portion closely coiled and umbonate, while the later portion uncoiled. The chambers are not inflated and the sutures are indistinct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFFBFFBAFF3D9DC569C67F59" blockId="22.[151,756,257,568]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFFBFFBAFF3D9DC568C57CF8" bold="true" box="[151,456,385,409]" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">Stratigraphic distribution:</emphasis>
It is recorded in the Austin Chalk of Leonard Fannin County, Texas by CUSHMAN (1927, 1946). It is recorded in the Maastrichtian and Paleocene in Southwestern Desert in 
<collectingCountry id="32CB7663FFFBFFBAFD909DA66B777C9B" box="[570,634,482,506]" name="Egypt" pageId="22" pageNumber="36">Egypt</collectingCountry>
by LUGER (1985). It is recorded in Sudr Chalk of the Esh El Mallaha area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
